\f1\fs26 \cf2 \cb3 How does the succession of sediment layers in marine sediment cores reflect the history of sedimentation in the ocean, and how in what respects can it provide a record of past oceanographic conditions?\
\
The succession of sediment layers in marine sediment cores reflects the history of the processes that sediment under went throughout the ocean in order to be preserved. In general, Abyssal clays dominate the deeper ocean regions, then carbonate oozes are dominate in temperate, tropical climates at depths less than 5 km. Siliceous oozes dominate the highly active waters near the in the Central Pacific and north of Antarctica, and terrigenous sediments dominate the continental margins and high altitude waters with ice cover. Age and thickness of sediments generally increases away from ridges. Thus, by observing the types of sediments layered in a core, we can understand the types of processes those layers underwent, and the kind of time frame they were formed in. \
